Custom queries in JPA can be written using JPQL (Java Persistence Query Language), native SQL, or Criteria API. The @Query annotation is the most common approach.

**1. Using @Query with JPQL (Recommended)**:

```java
public interface ProductRepository extends JpaRepository<Product, Long> {
    // Simple JPQL query
    @Query("SELECT p FROM Product p WHERE p.price > :minPrice")
    List<Product> findExpensiveProducts(@Param("minPrice") BigDecimal minPrice);

    // Multiple parameters
    @Query("""
        SELECT p FROM Product p 
        WHERE p.category = :category 
        AND p.price BETWEEN :minPrice AND :maxPrice
        ORDER BY p.name
    """)
    List<Product> findByPriceRange(
        @Param("category") String category,
        @Param("minPrice") BigDecimal minPrice,
        @Param("maxPrice") BigDecimal maxPrice);

    // With aggregation
    @Query("SELECT AVG(p.price) FROM Product p WHERE p.category = :category")
    Double getAveragePrice(@Param("category") String category);

    // Boolean result
    @Query("SELECT CASE WHEN COUNT(p) > 0 THEN true ELSE false END " +
           "FROM Product p WHERE p.sku = :sku")
    boolean existsBySku(@Param("sku") String sku);

    // Using JOIN
    @Query("""
        SELECT p FROM Product p 
        JOIN p.category c 
        WHERE c.name = :categoryName
    """)
    List<Product> findByCategory(@Param("categoryName") String categoryName);

    // GROUP BY and HAVING
    @Query("""
        SELECT c.name, COUNT(p) as productCount 
        FROM Product p 
        JOIN p.category c 
        GROUP BY c.id, c.name 
        HAVING COUNT(p) > :minCount
    """)
    List<Object[]> getCategoriesWithMinProducts(@Param("minCount") long minCount);
}
```

